body:
This is not quite a bug, but it has surprised me twice, so I figured I'd open an issue.

Consider the following code:

```
struct Boop {
    i: usize
}

impl Boop {
    fn next(&self) -> Boop {
        let mut out = self.clone();
        out.i += 1;
        return out;
    }
}
```

This fails to compile with the error message
```
 --> src/main.rs:9:16
  |
9 |         return out;
  |                ^^^ expected struct `Boop`, found &Boop
  |
  = note: expected type `Boop`
             found type `&Boop`
```

If you add `#[derive(Clone)]` to the `struct` definition, then it works, but that's a weirdly non-local change that's not hinted at by the error.  Could the compiler's error message be more helpful?

```rustc --version --verbose
rustc 1.29.1 (b801ae664 2018-09-20)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: b801ae66425cf7c3c71052b19ef8f145b0d0513d
commit-date: 2018-09-20
host: x86_64-apple-darwin
release: 1.29.1
LLVM version: 7.0```
